{
  "text": "In this context it is interesting to note that there is growing evidence for metals in the moderately overdense intergalactic medium (IGM) up to redshifts z \u223c 5 or so (cf. [CITATION_1] and references therein). The metals detected in the IGM can only have been synthesized by stars in galaxies, and galactic outflows energized by supernovae (SNe) are the primary means by which they can be transported from galaxies into the IGM. If galactic ISM is also magnetized due to some form of dynamo action, then such outflows will also transport magnetic fields into the IGM. One can roughly estimate the IGM field resulting from such outflows, by using magnetic flux conservation under spherically symmetric expansion; that is B seed \u2243 (\u03c1 IGM /\u03c1 ISM ) 2/3 B gal . For B gal \u2243 3\u00b5G, and \u03c1 IGM /\u03c1 ISM \u2243 10 \u22126 , one gets B seed \u2243 0.3 nG. In a similar fashion outflows from AGN can also transport magnetized plasma into the IGM.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "17965789"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "17965789": {
      "title": "How did the IGM become enriched?",
      "abstract": "The enrichment of the intergalactic medium with heavy elements is a process that lies at the nexus of poorly-understood aspects of physical cosmology. We review current understanding of the processes that may remove metals from galaxies, the basic predictions of these models, the key observational constraints on enrichment, and how intergalactic enrichment may be used to test cosmological simulations."
    }
  }
}